access the Profile directly.

which ensures the incognito-ness of the request always matches

the page it was triggered from (e.g. you do not have an Incognito

tab trying to trigger a non-incognito Payment request). Thus, use

the existing Profile reference.

entry.content:

origin to its quad in the viewport. This computation is currently

named element is an inline. It is relative to the named inline element's

container instead. Fix that by removing this offset from the same API

above.

entry.title: Update AccessibilityState touch exploration flag to manual calculation
entry.content:
This CL updates the isTouchExplorationEnabled state in the Chrome

AccessibilityState class to use a check of both the CAPABILITY and the

FLAG for touch exploration.



Before this CL, if a user toggled accessibility on and then off, it was

possible to get into an incorrect state. This would happen because in

the updateAccessibilityServices method, the call to

sAccessibilityManager.isTouchExplorationEnabled could return true, even

though all services were off (this is presumably because of the same

underlying conditions that make Chrome want to do an async manual

calculation, i.e. enabled vs running services out-of-sync as the service

is shutting down, in the attached bug TalkBack). When a downstream

client requests the accessibility state of Chrome, then Chrome, which

has cached its previously calculated value, would return true for the

isTouchExplorationEnabled call, signaling accessibility services are

running. However no accessibility services are running, and downstream

clients create IllegalStateExceptions in the framework by calling

accessibility methods.



There are a few ways in which to address this. One option would be that

we always return sAccessibilityManager.isTouchExplorationEnabled rather

than keeping it as part of the AccessibilityState's state management.

Another option would be to update the calculation of the state variable

to check if the value returned from sAccessibilityManager makes sense.

(e.g. if we know that the running and enabled services are in sync, and

they are both empty, then we know that isTouchExplorationEnabled is

not true). Finally, we could update the calculation of the state

variable to compare to the bit flags directly, this way we do not give

an incorrect value, and we know it was calculated once the system had

settled into a stable state. This CL takes the final approach.



We also add a flag, which we enable by default, that we guard this

change behind so that we can turn it off if needed.

entry.title: Ensure new_rfh_origin used in DisableThirdPartyStoragePartitioning check
entry.content:
In RenderFrameHostImpl::IsThirdPartyStoragePartitioningEnabled, we use the ancestor chain to compile a list of third-party origins that should be checked for the DisableThirdPartyStoragePartitioning deprecation trial.



In https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=1498580, we discovered that this function was returning "false" too early, thereby creating first-party keys that should have been third-party.



When compiling the ancestor chain, we forgot to use the new_rfh_origin passed into the function rather than "this->GetLastCommittedOrigin()", which produces incorrect results when the RenderFrameHost is reused (in some scenarios, which seemed to reliably reproduce in this colab).



This CL fixes that issue, and has been manually verified to fix the initial colab bug report.

entry.title: [ios] Fix slightly blurry unpinned Fakebox text
entry.content:
Prior to this change, the Fakebox font was set for the size that the

text should be when the Fakebox is pinned. As the Fakebox became

unpinned, a scale transform was applied to make the text bigger. But

a scale transform just scales up a raster image of the text which

resulted in slightly blurry text.



With this change, one font is used (without scaling) when the Fakebox is

pinned, and another larger font used when the Fakebox is not pinned.

When it is transitioning / animating, the larger font is used with a

scale-down transform. This results in text that is never blurry yet can

smoothly transition from bigger to smaller.

https://screenshot.googleplex.com/9ffL7cxw9ugCL5j



Screenshot without the fix:

entry.title: [Autofill] Remove AutofillDriver::RendererIsAvailable()
entry.content:
RendererIsAvailable() was introduced in [1] before Autofill used Mojo.

The checks appear not to be effective today:



RendererIsAvailable() checks whether RFHIplm::render_view_host_ is

non-nullptr. This is always the case because render_view_host_ is a

scoped_refptr which, according to its documentation,

> is kept alive as long as any RenderFrameHosts or

> RenderFrameProxyHosts are using it.



Perhaps a more useful implementation of RendererIsAvailable() would

call RFH::IsRenderFrameLive(). That seems redundant, too, because

ContentAutofillDriverFactory creates a driver only if

RFH::IsRenderFrameLive(), and destroys the driver on

RenderFrameDeleted().



[1] https://chromiumcodereview.appspot.com/17572015

entry.title: [mullet m2] DidAcceptSuggestion handles sub-popups.
entry.content:
The position param passed to ExternalDelegate::DidAcceptSuggestion

is not taking into account the fact that we now have sub-popups.

This has a few problems:



1. The metrics emitted are not representing what they should.

SuggestionAccepted[1] metric assumes only one level, which tells us

how well we are sorting suggestions, meaning the more often the

user chooses suggestions with position=0, the better we sorted.

However, because users can choose to fill the whole form (fillEverything) from the second level, the position is

given as 7, even tough the second level could have been open

from the first suggestion.



2. It does not allow us to measure the usage in the second/third level.



The solution is to update ExternalDelegate::DidAcceptSuggestion

inside the delegate, so that we can have the expected behaviour depending on the "sub_popup_level".



This CL is a no-op, I will start passing the sub_popup_level

information and fix the metric emission in a follow up.



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:components/autofill/core/browser/metrics/suggestions_list_metrics.cc;drc=719c18366c0226fa751f38693b00f822d1b7ea9b;l=34

entry.title: PlzDedicatedWorker: Add the field trial testing config.
entry.content:
For ease of detecting changes that do not work well with

PlzDedicatedWorker, let me add the field trial testing config

with the PlzDedicatedWorker enabled.



We followed the past attempt to update the field trial testing config:

https://chromium.googlesource.com/chromium/src/+/c8900237101eff877c5eee2c1b17928c7f1abab9

i.e.

- move expectation files in /web_tests/virtual/plz-dedicated-worker

to the non-virtual directory.

- delete dedicated-worker-service-worker-interception.html that is not

spec-compatible behavior which was added at

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/1059979

- delete dedicated-worker-reporting.html because COEP reports are sent

to worker's ReportingObserver API after PlzDedicatedWorker. Before

PlzDedicatedWorker, reports are sent to ancestor frame's

ReportingObserver but it's not spec compatible.

- delete use-counter-out-of-scope-worker.html, which was used for

measuring the impact of PlzDedicatedWorker ship for intent-to-ship.

- update "resource.type: other" to "resource.type: script".

- delete/merge "virtual/plz-dedicated-worker" expectation lines in

TestExpectations.



Removal of the "virtual/plz-dedicated-worker" directory will be

done in the future CL.
